SUMMARIZER="C">     

Elizabeth Taylor has recovered from a life-threatening case of
pneumonia. A lung specialist treating her said her life was in danger
over the weekend, and that she is over the worst but she is not yet
"out of the woods". There have been consistent rumors about AIDS, but
her doctors said that there is nothing to suggest AIDS or cancer. The
actress had earlier denied that she had AIDS. Marie Burton-Carson,
Liza Todd-Tivey, and Christopher and Michael Wilding, her four
children from three marriages, have been with her.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d24"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA042790-0205"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="C">     

Liz Taylor has been plagued by health woes since 1945 when she fell
from a horse during the filming of "National Velvet". She has endured
about 20 major operations on her back, appendix, eyes and
teeth. Respiratory ailments have been a recurring problem. She has
survived seven rocky marriages to six men, and addictions to alcohol,
painkillers and food. In 1983 and again in 1988 she underwent
addiction treatment at the Betty Ford Clinic Her many setbacks have
added to her stardom, and she has never attracted more attention than
she has been getting during her current hospitalization.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d24"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA051190-0185"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="C">     

Elizabeth Taylor has been hospitalized for over four weeks. There are
new complications in her case that will keep her in St John's Hospital
and Health Center for another six weeks. She was recovering nicely
from the viral pneumonia that had put her life in danger, but now has
contracted a bacterial pneumonia, a strain that is considered much
less serious than viral because antibiotics are effective against
bacteria but not against viruses. She has also developed a blood
infection known as yeast, and will remain in the hospital for
intravenous therapy.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d24"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900511-0159"
